>
  <p>
    A <strong>provider</strong> turns gode's normalized turn into a model call and streams
    the response back as events. Providers implement a common Go interface so the runner
    does not need to know which model is behind it.
  </p>

  <h2>Adapters</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>OpenAI / Codex</strong> — primary provider. Multi-turn tool result continuation, the OpenAI Responses API, image inputs, and compaction.</li>
    <li><strong>Anthropic Claude</strong> — Go SDK adapter, in active development. Image input serialization is already in place.</li>
    <li><strong>Mock</strong> — deterministic provider for tests, ACP integration runs, and offline development.</li>
    <li><strong>Custom chat-completions models</strong> — supported via the chat-completions provider for self-hosted or alternative endpoints.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Picking one</h2>
  <pre><code>go run ./cmd/gode acp \
  --workspace "$PWD" \
  --data-dir "$HOME/.gode" \
  --provider openai \
  --model gpt-5.5</code></pre>

  <p>For offline testing:</p>
  <pre><code>go run ./cmd/gode acp --provider mock --auto-approve</code></pre>

  <h2>What the interface guarantees</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Streaming text deltas as events on the bus.</li>
    <li>Structured tool calls with stable identifiers across the turn.</li>
    <li>Cancellation via context — when the user cancels, the provider call stops promptly.</li>
    <li>Image inputs serialized into the format each provider expects.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Adding a provider</strong> is a matter of implementing the provider interface
    and wiring its construction into the CLI. The runner does not change.
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
